The most ambitious lawn mowing works for farmers are planned in Talsi road district for a total of 28 roads 637 hiking kilometres, Valmiera road area for 20 roads 432 hiking kilometres, and Alūksne for 17 roads 384 hiking kilometres.
As already reported, in June the company completed grass mowing on the main and most important regional asphalted roads of the country, but on smaller regional roads and on local roads VAS Latvian road maintainer planned to entrust part of the mowing work to farmers.
"We are able to use the funds allocated to road maintenance works more efficiently, while at the same time giving farmers the opportunity to fully load the machinery and earn money", says Vladimirs Kononovs, Chairman of the Board of SJSC Latvia Road maintainer.
The closing date for the submission of tenders shall be 22 August.
Ombudsman: Demagogy on compulsory health insurance model with additional financial burden on citizens does not hold any criticism.
Any demagogy on compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and heavy payment burden on citizens, does not hold any criticism, considers the Ombudsman Juris Jansons.
Jansons met with Health Minister Anda Chaks today to discuss the situation in the health sector.
After the meeting, Jansons told journalists that the financing model proposed by the Minister for Health was sustainable and developed in the health care system, making it more accessible to patients.
He noted, however, that in this case there was a need to talk about additional funding for healthcare, which is currently insufficient.
Jansons also stressed that any demagogy on compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and heavy burden of payment on citizens, did not hold any criticism, especially when calling on the Dutch model.
Jansons said that the Netherlands devotes 11% of gross domestic product to health, while Latvia only 3%.
The Government and Parliament must therefore be responsible enough to understand that this freezing point must rise, the Ombudsman said, and added that otherwise the model proposed by the Ministry of Health (MH) would not work.
Čakša thanked the Ombudsman for his support and pointed out that the main concern is that the patient should receive a doctor, which in turn means that the healthcare system needs additional funding.
The Minister pointed out, however, that with the additional EUR 35 million planned next year, it will only be possible to do the most acute cases regarding oncological patients and the remuneration of maternity specialists.
As a result, the MoU has developed a plan and submitted a request for an additional €41 million to be allocated to health care in order to reduce the waiting lists for specialists and for examinations.
"The question of priorities whether or not it will have the means," said Chang.
This amount, however, does not include an increase in the remuneration of medical professionals.
Commenting on the fact that the medical profession is not thrilled that all three options of the healthcare financing model, including the one which provides for an additional payment to patients, are being driven by the MM for government scrutiny, he said that by driving all three models, the government is being given the opportunity to choose.
Jansons also added that by directing all three models, it is possible to clearly show that Latvia is not ready to impose additional burden on the population.
As already reported, the Ministry of Health will defend the option of the health care financing model, which does not envisage an overall increase in the tax burden, but requires a part of the social tax to be passed on to health, says the conceptual summary of the report "On the change of the financing model of the Latvian health care system".
At the same time, the Ministry indicated that the best version of the model for financing health care will be chosen as a result of discussions by the end of September.
