How to prepare for the family photo session.
The summer is still in full swing, and immediately another school year, which families tend to capture in photo memories, comes.
To make the pictures look happy and beautiful, it is worth considering how to prepare for the photo session in advance.
Ihappymama's advice is provided by the mother of many children Aleksandra Nesterenko and the professional photographer Marina Levickaja.
You have to take pictures of nature, because it is much more natural and harmonious.
The study makes it much harder for children to feel and relax.
It is recommended to choose a uniform dress style for the whole family, preferably in the same colour range.
For example, Alexandra says that she chooses clothing for all six members of her family so that the clothes are no more than three shades of color and as few inscriptions as possible on the clothing.
Don't forget about the mood.
Enjoy joking, playing, but never yelling or psychiatism if the children are not as obedient as they would like.
And here's the next advice from a professional photographer's douche!
You have to understand exactly what you want to capture during the photo session and tell the photographer about it.
For some, they will be beautiful, neat children and an ideal family picture, for others – "life is what it is like", namely, a desire to see real, genuine emotions in the pictures, or, as a photographer loves to say, "refugee backs", "eyes closed", "stretched nose".
Of course, it happens that someone also wants "two in one", but this happens rarely.
In any case, when you go to the photo session, you have to understand that it's just a couple of hours from your life, and the less you get a sign, the better.
You're yourself -- there's no strong mom who's working, cooking, raising, and so on, and not an old dad who's constantly talking on the phone.
And neither is the man who lives in you behind some unknown shell.
Be family, remember how great it is to hug each other, smile at your own and joke.
And then the photographer's task will be to capture the right moments for the emotions that prevail among you.
If you have chosen a photographer, trust him.
Stop 250 times asking for a show of what has happened, listen to his advice in choosing clothes, a place for better shots.
Tilt and iron all the clothes you need in advance so that you do not need to do so on the day of the photo session.
Plan the route and think about how much time you will need to get to the place of the photo session (especially if the photography takes place in the studio and the time is limited).
If you have little children, then choose the time of the photo session that corresponds to the day of the baby’s day so that it doesn’t happen when the baby sleeps.
And, of course, do not forget to take with your children food, cookies, water and a favorite toy (use the sweets and sweets only in extreme situations).
In preparation for Dad, he may need to wear his socks, but this is not usually written in such tips, and only photographers know what the problem is, admits Marina.
Don't drink a lot of water before you take a photo session and sleep well before that.
And it would be advisable to have some entertainment together after the photo session.
Go to the amusement park, eat some ice cream, take a ride with roller skates, which family likes more.
This will give you great pictures and pleasant memories of the day spent together.
Krasnopurovs and Fadejeva: raising the minimum wage - a miracle or a brake for the economy?
The question of raising the minimum wage in public debates has almost the status of holy cow: either support the raising or mention of some unspeakable, general phrases.
In view of the significant increase in the risk of economic stagnation (we barely avoided technical recession), it is important to stress that raising the minimum wage is not a miracle that will reduce income inequality with one hint, bring Latvian salaries closer to the level of Western Europe and fill the state budget.
On the contrary, if the minimum wage is raised too much, it does more harm than good because raising it reduces the competitiveness and employment of businesses, especially in sectors and low-income regions.
At first glance, it seems that, despite several increases in minimum wages in the post-crisis period, the minimum wage in Latvia is not so high that raising the usual number of tens of euros per year would significantly weaken the competitiveness of companies - just 370 euros, while in some European Union (EU) countries the minimum wage is around one and a half thousand.
However, a different picture can be seen if we compare it with the average salary in the country (%) - the minimum wage in Latvia (44%) exceeds the EU average.
Since Latvia's share of minimum wages is substantially higher than in neighbouring countries (Latvia - 17%, Lithuania - 11%, Estonia - 6%[1]), a similar rise in minimum wages is binding for most companies.
According to the results of the survey of Latvijas Banka companies, one in five Latvian companies replied that, as the minimum wage increased at the beginning of 2014, it was important or very important for it to increase the prices of products.
This means, firstly, that the rise in the minimum wage was partly financed by consumers (i.e. residents of Latvia); secondly, the rise in prices for several companies meant loss of competitiveness both in the domestic market and abroad (i.e., increased imports and limited exports).
Due to weaker competitiveness and shrinking production volumes, it was important for almost every fifteen Latvian companies to lay off their employees (which means higher unemployment and emigration).
In addition, almost one in eleven companies replied that, as a result of raising the minimum wage, it was important for him to limit the recruitment of new employees.
It is worth remembering that in 2011-2013 the minimum wage in Latvia did not change.
Therefore, even if, when assessing the raising of the 2014 minimum wage, one in five companies noted the improvement of productivity as important, this does not mean that a similar result could be expected in 2017 as well (the fourth increase in the minimum wage in a row could reduce productivity growth opportunities).
Another important result is that, as a result of the rise in minimum wages, it was also important for several companies to increase the remuneration of employees earning more than the minimum wage.
Thus, the impact of the minimum wage was significant even for companies where no employees received the minimum wage.
In recent years, the rise in minimum wages in all three Baltic States exceeded the increase in nominal productivity (real productivity + inflation).
Thus, a further increase in the minimum wage (even though the overall rather low level in terms of the euro) which is not justified by productivity growth will have a negative impact on the competitiveness and employment of enterprises.
When assessing the justification for raising the minimum wage, it is not enough to analyse the average economic indicators.
It is also necessary to assess whether raising the minimum wage is "obstructable" in the sectors and regions where the minimum wage is most commonly used.
The results of the survey of the Bank of Latvia show that the highest concentration of employees with minimum wages is in small companies (the number of employees is between 10 and 19 employees; 25%).
At the end of 2013, the share of employees with minimum wages was higher in industry and services sectors (16% and 19% respectively) than in trade (15%), construction (11%) and financial and insurance sectors (2%).
On the other hand, for Latgale, where the minimum wage is 64% of the average wage (and more than two thirds of the average wage in the private sector), its further rise may be more damaging by reducing labour demand (i.e. maintaining already high unemployment) and promoting the sustainability of the shadow economy.
There are some signs that the significant rises in the minimum wage implemented in 2014-2015 (by 27% in total) have slowed the development of Latgale.
For example, Latgale is the only region in Latvia where unemployment was higher in 2015 than in 2013.
It should be noted that there is no region in Estonia and Lithuania that is so far lagging behind in terms of average wages from the rest of the country.
In Estonia, for example, the average wage in all regions is at least twice the national minimum wage.
In Lithuania, the lowest wages are in the Taurage region, but also there, the minimum wage in 2015 was 54% of the average wage (after two rapid increases in the minimum wage in 2016, this figure could reach 58%).
The public debate has occasionally called for the minimum wage to be raised to 68% of the average wage in the country (see, for example, here) lacks economic justification, and this cannot be achieved either in the short term or in the long term.
Firstly, such a high figure from the average salary, or even as close to it, is not in any EU country.
Secondly, it would mean raising the minimum wage above the average wage in several sectors of the economy (which would mean the bankruptcy and mass redundancies of companies in these sectors), for example, in the production of clothing, leather products, fish processing, catering services, as well as in veterinary services; moreover, it is more than the current average salary in the private sector of Latgale.
Raising the minimum wage from January 2017 to EUR 400-410 per month, as currently proposed by the Ministry of Welfare, would make the minimum wage in Latvia (% of the average wage) one of the highest in the EU.
If nominal productivity increases by 4% and the minimum wage at least twice as fast, this has clearly negative consequences for the competitiveness and employment of businesses.
Such negative consequences will be most common in sectors and regions where the current minimum wage level is often used, for example, in Latgale.
The fact that a substantial rise in the minimum wage cannot currently be tolerated means that other mechanisms should be used to support low-wage recipients.
An immediate effect can be achieved by travelling with a non-taxable minimum of personal income tax (within the limits of the budget).
Insufficient level of education, inadequate education and poor quality of education, as well as unsatisfactory health status (often due to the cost of medical services and long queues) are among the real causes of income inequality.
During the survey 521 replies of the Latvian company were obtained on the response to the rise in the minimum wage that took place in January 2014.
The survey was carried out within the framework of the Wage Dynamics Network (WDN) project.
These figures represent companies with a minimum number of employees of 10.
This also explains the low proportion of employees with minimum wages in construction.
