The police rescue the baby from overheating in the car; the parents are threatened by court action.
In Riga yesterday, municipal policemen rescued the baby from a hot car, while the parents threatened the police with court works about the broken car glass, LETA informed the Riga Municipal Police (RPP).
Yesterday, a excited man came to the patrol, who told him that he noticed a car in the Spice parking lot in which an infant was present for half an hour without the presence of adults.
On arriving at the scene, an eyewitnessed car was found, standing in the sun.
In the front passenger seat there was a child seat in which the infant was present.
It was the rays of the sun that shone on the child.
The baby screamed loudly, breathed intensely, and his face was red and sweaty.
Given that the owner of the vehicle was not present on the spot, an immediate decision has been taken to break the rear glass of the car in order not to endanger the health and life of the infant.
The child with the entire seat is highlighted from the hot vehicle, and called medical staff.
The child breathed the shallow, the skin was reddish and hot, so until the doctors arrived, the guards placed a cool compress on their forehead.
Medical doctors and parents arrived almost simultaneously at the scene.
When the baby’s father saw the broken window on his vehicle, he remained aggressive and the medical staff were not allowed to reach the child.
Discussions with parents explain that a child under the age of 7 is forbidden to leave one unattended.
In addition, the child was left in a life - threatening environment.
After the discussion, the medical staff looked at the victim and found that hospitalization was not necessary.
The children’s parents refused to give any explanation about what had happened and threatened with judicial work on the broken car glass.
There was no indication that they were under the influence of alcohol or could otherwise harm the child during the conversation, so the baby less than four months old was taken to care for both.
The case materials have been sent to the Children’s Crime Prevention Division, whose employees will assess parental responsibility.
The RMP reminds us that even if the outside is not very hot, a car left in the sun heats up very quickly.
If a child or a pet is left in such a car, it can endanger their lives.
