Behind Tata Steel UK, the pension trustees said that the scheme could be restructured without participating in the Pension Protection Fund (PFF), increasing the company's chances of concluding a rescue transaction.
The pension scheme for the British steel sector has a liability of GBP 15 billion and an estimated deficit of at least GBP 700 million, creating a serious impediment to the conclusion of a rescue transaction between Tata Steel UK and Port Talbot Steelworks in Wales.
Tata Steel is increasingly convinced of securing the future of the British business, which employs 11 000 people, following negotiations with the Minister of Economy and the pension regulator.
The company plans to combine its European activities, including the British business with ThyssenKrupp, a German conglomerate.
