Macy's will close 100 stores.
The supermarket giant Macy's on Thursday announced its plans to close 100 shops, which is a dramatic step towards helping the store chain to get ahead of the potentially meticulous problems: in America, it claims to be an online shopping era for too many stores.
Macy's regularly reduces its store portfolio, often closing several dozens of under-performing stores immediately after the annual holiday fever.
However, with its summer announcement that it will close 15 per cent of its 728 outlets, the chains of stores seem to have taken a much more aggressive stance than many similar retail players in terms of reducing the number of their shops, adapting to a very changing shopping environment.
Pedestrians and buyers go past the Macy's store in New York.
The retail giant announces that he plans to close 100 shops.
Macy's has many reasons to try to change something: many of its shops are located in small regional shopping centres, as the number of buyers has been particularly affected by the boom in e-commerce.
The retail sector as a whole has faced more difficult times, as buyers increasingly prefer lower price retailers such as T.J.Maxx and fast fashion players such as H&M to buy clothes.
These factors, along with short-term difficulties such as ever smaller international tourist spending and seasonal weather conditions that Macy's has placed in a fragile situation that has already lasted for more than a year.
On Thursday, the company announced that its comparable sales in the last quarter had dropped by 2.6 percent, a rather weak indicator, which was nevertheless an improvement given the very poor 6.1 percent drop in the year-on-year, which was found in the previous quarter.
The retailer's income was USD 5.87 billion (7.64 billion Canadian dollars), 3.9 percent less than in the same period last year.
Macy's stated that closing the shops would cost it about USD 1 billion in terms of annual turnover.
And closing such a large number of shops at the same time could be seen as a recognition of the collapse of the retailer.
However, the value of the company's shares dropped by 17 percent on Thursday, which indicates that investors perceive this move as a proactive measure that tells about a stronger future for Macy's.
In a way, the fact that Macy's reduces the number of stores should not be a surprise.
The Director-General of the retailer, Terry Lundgreen, said earlier that there are quite simply too many shops in the chain.
Top managers have for some time said that they have adopted a new strategy, which places particular emphasis on 150 of its most profitable shops, trying to achieve higher sales in already profitable outlets.
Jeff Janette, director of Macy's, who has been appointed instead of Lundgren since 2017, said in his statement almost all the shops that the company intends to close are those where sales and profitability slide down.
"We are aware that we do not yet get an adequate return on investment in these outlets, and there is often no level of customer shopping experience that reflects our efforts in relation to the Macy's brand," Janette said.
The company announced that it would present a list of shops that would be closed later.
Macy's said that it was still decided on the closing shops and that therefore it was not yet clear how many workers would be made redundant.
The retailer will not leave the main markets where it currently has shops completely, but it will think about closing those shops that are located in less active places.
