So, is the real long and hard struggle for equality between women finally over?
Hillary Clinton is ready to be President of the United States at any time, but in the area of religion, women's leadership is still a controversial issue.
Okay, not completely.
In the religious field, women's leadership remains a controversial issue.
Last week, Pope Francis announced the creation of a new commission to assess whether women should be consecrated in a diacons round in the Catholic Church.
The Anglican Church consecrated Libya Lane as the first woman-bishop in January 2015, but it was only after a failed attempt in 2012.
While the reform of the Jewish movement has been used as a rabbinic for women since the early 1970s and in the conservative movement since the early 1980s, the concept of the female rabbinic is still very fiercely opposed in orthodox Judaism.
In November 2015, the American Orthodox rabbinic Council published a rather harsh message in its third attempt to halt the ever-increasing wave of support for the rabbinic treatment of Orthodox women that the concept of female rabbinic is contrary to the law.
Not without irony, when Hillary Clinton was nominated as President-in-Office of the Democrats, a group of American leading Orthodox rabbis opposed to female ordination launched a series of "discussions" on this controversial issue.
Why is there such a difference between secular and sacred?
Orthodoxal Judaism, like most other religions, is looking for stability in what it considers to be long-standing traditional values.
This is reflected in the ability to resist pressure to adapt to a changing society.
Those who oppose female ordination do so on the grounds that it is not "traditional."
However, taking over with the preservation of traditions in this way has a price.
And the price of such one-sided thinking can paradoxically undermine the tradition itself by taking away from the traditional community the oxygen it needs to maintain its vitality.
In the book "August Firearms", in the military history of World War I, Barbara Tachman emphasizes the danger of giving priority to the tradition of what has become known as "the tragedy of red trousers."
Until the outbreak of World War I, when war moved from war to more severe artillery from further distance, it became profitable to hide soldiers as long as possible.
British and German armies reacted to these changes by replacing their bright uniforms with boring grey and brown.
French soldiers, however, still wore the same red hats and trousers that made them easy for purposes.
The French Minister of War Affairs, Adolf Messymi, suggested that the armies under his command could do the same, was treated with ridicule and opposition.
Red trousers reflected the pride and prestige of the army, and the military traditionals were not prepared to give up.
Speaking in parliament, former Minister for War Affairs Eijens Etyens spoke on behalf of France.
"Rejecting the red pants?" he exclaimed.
Never!
"It's the inexpressive and idiotic appendix at the most visible of all colors," then wrote Messy, "it was supposed to have a bad effect."
Faith leaders who are fighting for the inclusion of women in leading religious roles could fall into the same trap.
Focusing solely on "traditional" religion, rather than asking the important question: "What changes are needed for religion to flourish?" they risk losing about 50 percent of their followers.
They also take away from the whole community the talent, skills and enthusiasm that women would otherwise bring.
To insist that men continue to wear trousers when it comes to religion may be traditional, but as the destruction of red trousers shows, it may not be worth it.
Dina Breivere is a founder of JOFA (Women's Orthodox Feminist Association) in Great Britain and an orthodox rabbinic student at Yashivata Maharate in New York.
