Lurda is about to pick up pilgrims in the shadow of attack
During the annual Catholic pilgrimage, people gather at the Sanctuary of Lurda Our Lady.
France’s security forces are very alert, since thousands of Catholics gather at Lurda’s annual pilgrimage in the shadow of several acts of terror.
On August 15, each year, tens of thousands of people gather at the temple at the foot of the Pyrenees Mountains to celebrate the arrival of the virgin Mary in heaven.
This year's pilgrimage takes place at a time when Catholics have been shocked by the murder of an elderly French priest on 26 July by two Islamic extremists who invaded a church in the north of France during the Mass and cut his throat.
Jacques Amel's murder took place two weeks after a Tunisian -- investigators say he's been radicalized by Jihadists' online videos,--embled by a truck in the Bastille Day crowd of Riviera, Nice, killing 85 people.
After three major attacks in 18 months, many French people are cautious about attending public events.
The number of tourists fell dramatically, and the authorities feared that the number of pilgrims this year would fall rapidly.
However, fear of mass withdrawals did not materialize -- and some organisers say that even the influx of visitors' applications at the last minute has been observed.
Around 25 000 believers are expected to arrive, including a delegation from large groups from Italy and Belgium and about 200 from the Eastern Brethren, the Orthodox.
Many pilgrims have declared that they will not be intimidated.
"We do not intend to stop living," a 66-year-old visitor Christian said to AFP, describing prayer as "the only weapon" in the fight against violence.
"It is important to show that life continues," said Matier Gvinar - one of the coordinators.
We will not give up our faith, our beliefs, and our way of life simply because some fanatics are trying to sow fear.
Due to concerns about safety in France, a number of large-scale measures have been lifted since the attack in Nice, including the huge stock market in the northern city of Lille and the European cycling championship on the highway, which was due to take place in Nice in September.
"Last week I lived in fear that my phone would call in a single call to withdraw applications," said Fabien Légersne, a priest in charge of official pilgrimage last weekend.
"On the contrary, it seems that the attacks have mobilised the believers," he said and announced the inflow of last minute applications.
The head of the professional association of local hotel workers, Christian Žel, confirmed an "enhanced interest" in pilgrimage after the attacks.
Around the sacred place where the virgin Mary appeared in 1858 to the poor shepherd Bernadete Subiru, there were extremely strict security measures.
Some 250 policemen and two dozen soldiers have been assigned for protection, including bomb neutralization experts and explosives search dogs.
The bags were checked at the entrance, and the number of access points was reduced from twelve to three.
Catherine Simcox, who traveled from northeastern England to Lurda at the beginning of this month, described the increased security measures.
"By Thursday morning there were armed guards in the shrines, and then through the gate (with metal barriers) could enter only one by one, as well as were searched bags," she said in The Local.
"This all frightened my three children who were used to Lurda, and it was hard not to frighten them when they asked why it was so," she said.
It has not ruined my impressions, but it saddened me that it was necessary, and I realized that many people were comforted by these measures.
The Friday opening procession route has also been shortened – instead of starting in Lurda and moving on to the shrine, it will begin and end in the shrine.
Other measures include the closure of the airspace for flights over Lurda, the closure of streets near the traffic shrine and the replacement of waste bins for transparent plastic bags.
On Saturday, the French Minister for the Interior, Bernārs Kazenevs, will check security measures.
About six million people travel to Lurda a year, making it one of the largest Catholic pilgrimage destinations in the world.
Many visitors lead relatives who are ill or disabled and who come to swim in a spring cave where Bernadette had seen Mary, believing in the healing properties of water.
Thierry Castijo, one of the organizers, described this year's gathering as "a little unusual" in view of "the threat as the roots seem to lie in France."
However, he claimed that this would not affect the quality and depth of their experiences.
François, a 58-year-old volunteer who helped sick pilgrims, admitted that in her opinion the presence of soldiers dressed in civil clothing was "a little depressing."
However, if it calms everyone down, it is good.
