The coast of New Caledonia is shaken by an earthquake of 7.2
On Friday, the coast of New Caledonia was shaken by an earthquake of 7.2 magnitudes, reported by seismologists, pointing out that there was no tsunami threat.
The earthquake epicentre was located at a depth of nine kilometres 109 kilometers east of New Caledonia at 1.26 Greenwich time (4.26 p.m. Latvian time), announced the U.S. Geological Research Centre.
The Pacific Cunami Alert Centre indicated that there are currently no warnings or recommendations in relation to the potential threat of tsunamis to the region.
"The landraces in this region, as is known, are not unusual, nor are activities recently unusual", said Senior seismologist Phil Camins of the research centre "Geoscience Australia".
It could potentially be felt on the islands of Vanuatu or New Caledonia, but I doubt that it is so powerful as to cause damage.
New Caledonia is located in "Fire Circle" - the area of Pacific tectonic activity, where earthquakes and volcanic eruptions occur frequently.
