According to the information provided by the laboratory, 121 samples were tested for Zika virus this year and nine of them were positive.
The first cases of Zika have been reported in Finland and Sweden in neighbouring countries of Estonia.
According to the Estonian Health Authority, no case of acute Zika virus infection has been recorded in the country and people do not need to test Zika virus in case of flu-like symptoms, but they should contact their family doctor.
We have found IgG (immunoglobulin G) antibodies that show that the subject is infected with Zika or a similar virus at some point.
"This does not mean that the patient has contracted Zika virus", explained Paul Naber, head of the infectious diseases department of the laboratory "Synlab".
Zika's virus is transmitted by mosquitoes of the genus Aedes.
